      <format>text/x-wiki</format>
      <text bytes="13512" xml:space="preserve">[[File:Pasta alla Norma (2563876877).jpg|thumb|The [[Catania|Catanese]] dish, [[pasta alla Norma]], is among Sicily's most historic and iconic.|alt=A plate of pasta with tomatoes, eggplant, basil, and cheese|300x300px]]
{{Italian cuisine}}

'''Sicilian cuisine''' is the style of cooking on the island of [[Sicily]]. It shows traces of all cultures that have existed on the island of Sicily over the last two millennia.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.umass.edu/journal/sicilyprogram/sicilianfoodhistory.html Sicilian food history] umass.edu&lt;/ref&gt; Although its cuisine has a lot in common with [[Italian cuisine]], Sicilian food also has [[Greek cuisine|Greek]], [[Spanish cuisine|Spanish]], [[French cuisine|French]] and [[Arab cuisine|Arab]] influences.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|url=http://www.tesorichicago.com/the-influences-ingredients-of-sicilian-cuisine/|title=The Influences &amp; Ingredients of Sicilian Cuisine - Tesori|date=2016-07-19|work=Tesori|access-date=2017-05-10|language=en-US}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The Sicilian cook [[Mithaecus]], born during 5th century BC, is credited with having brought knowledge of Sicilian gastronomy to [[Greece]]:&lt;ref&gt;Dalby (2003), p. 220; Hill and Wilkins (1996), pp. 144-148.&lt;/ref&gt; his cookbook was the first in Greek, therefore he was the earliest cookbook author in any language whose name is known.

==History==
[[Arab]] influences on Sicilian cuisine trace to the [[Emirate of Sicily|Arab domination of Sicily]] in the 10th and 11th centuries, &lt;ref name=&quot;Piras, 423&quot;&gt;Piras, 423.&lt;/ref&gt; and include the use of [[apricot]]s, [[sugar]], [[citrus]], sweet [[melon]]s, [[rice]], [[saffron]], [[raisin]]s, [[nutmeg]], [[clove]], [[Black pepper|pepper]], [[pine nut]]s and [[cinnamon]]. [[Normans]] influences are also found, such as in the fondness for [[meat]] dishes.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|url=http://www.etnasicilytouring.com/en/sicily/territory-custom/219-a-brief-history-of-sicilian-cuisine.html|title=A Brief History of Sicilian Cuisine|access-date=2017-05-10|language=en-GB}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[Jews|Jewish]] community, who lived in the island, also left their mark on the Sicilian cuisine, they were responsible for introducing garlic fried in olive oil into the sauce.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|date=2020-08-06|title=Storia della Cucina Siciliana: un'arte unica al mondo, fatta di gusto e tradizione|url=https://www.siciliafan.it/cucina-siciliana/|access-date=2020-09-10|website=Siciliafan|language=it-IT}}&lt;/ref&gt; Later, the [[Spain cuisine|Spanish]] introduced [[Columbian Exchange|numerous items from the New World]], including [[chocolate|cocoa]], [[maize]], [[Bell pepper|peppers]], [[Turkey (food)|turkey]], and [[tomato]]es, along with other [[produce]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Piras, 423&quot; /&gt;  [[Catania]], on the east coast, was initially [[Magna Græcia|settled by Greek colonists]],  who left a preference for [[Fish (food)|fish]], [[olive]]s, [[Vicia faba|broad beans]], [[pistachio|pistachios]] , and fresh vegetables. Much of the island's cuisine encourages the use of fresh vegetables such as [[eggplant]], [[Bell pepper|peppers]], and tomatoes, and fish such as [[tuna]], [[sea bream]], [[European seabass|sea bass]], [[cuttlefish]], and [[swordfish]]. In [[Trapani]] in the extreme western corner of the island, [[North African cuisine|North African]] influences are clear in the use of [[couscous]].

==Dishes==
{{see also|List of Sicilian dishes}}

===Starters===
The starters (called ''[[antipasti]]'') are an important aspect of Sicilian cuisine. Common Sicilian starters include [[caponata]] and gatò di patate (a kind of potato and cheese pie).

===Soups===
[[Maccu]] is a Sicilian [[soup]] and foodstuff prepared with [[Vicia faba|fava beans]] as a primary ingredient.&lt;ref name=&quot;Helstosky&quot;&gt;{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pk63U0ppWYAC&amp;pg=PA7 | title=Food Culture in the Mediterranean | publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group | author=Helstosky, Carol | year=2009 | pages=7 | isbn=0313346267}}&lt;/ref&gt; It is a [[Peasant foods|peasant food]]&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont0000rile | url-access=registration | title=The Oxford Companion to Italian Food | publisher=Oxford University Press | author=Riley, Gillian | year=2007 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont0000rile/page/501 501] | isbn=0198606176}}&lt;/ref&gt; and [[staple food|staple]]  that dates back to [[ancient history]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Helstosky&quot;/&gt; ''Maccu di San Giuseppe'' ([[English language|English]]: maccu of St. Joseph) is a traditional Sicilian dish that consists of various ingredients and maccu.&lt;ref name=&quot;Clarkson&quot;&gt;{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KOzYAgAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA262 | title=Food History Almanac | publisher=Rowman &amp; Littlefield | author=Clarkson, Janet | year=2013 | pages=262 | isbn=144222715X}}&lt;/ref&gt; The dish may be prepared on [[Saint Joseph's Day]] in Sicily, to clear out pantries and allow room for the spring's new crops of vegetables.&lt;ref name=&quot;Clarkson&quot;/&gt;

===Pasta===
Sicily is the oldest Italian and Western location on record where [[pasta]]  worked into long and thin form was part of the local cuisine. This dates back to around the 12th century, as attested by the [[Tabula Rogeriana]] of [[Muhammad al-Idrisi]], reporting some traditions about the [[Sicilian kingdom]].&lt;ref&gt;[[Spaghetti#cite note-2]]&lt;/ref&gt;

Spaghetti ai ricci (spaghetti prepared with sea urchin), [[pasta con le sarde]] (with sardines) and [[pasta alla Norma]] (a specialty that originated in Catania) are the most popular pasta dishes that are typically Sicilian. [[Cannelloni]] is another common dish. Another popular dish in eastern Sicily is pasta with [[capuliato]].

===Main dish===
After the pasta, the typical Sicilian menu includes a second or main dish (''secondi'') based on meat or fish. Main dishes based on seafood are [[couscous|couscous al pesce]] and Pesce spada alla ghiotta (Swordfish).

===Desserts and sweets===
{{see also|List of Italian desserts|List of Italian dishes#Desserts and pastry}}
Sweets are another specialty.  Examples include: [[frutta martorana]], [[pignolata|Pignolata of Messina]], [[buccellato]], [[cannoli]], [[granita]], [[cassata siciliana]] and the [[Crocetta of Caltanissetta]], a sweet that disappeared and was rediscovered in 2014.&lt;ref name=&quot;urlCaltanissetta riscopre le Crocette&quot;&gt;{{cite web| url =http://tcsnews.tv/news/8469/Caltanissetta-riscopre-le-crocette| title =Caltanissetta riscopre le &quot;Crocette&quot;| date =2014-08-26| language =it| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20140924042203/http://tcsnews.tv/news/8469/Caltanissetta-riscopre-le-crocette| archivedate =2014-09-24}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Candy in Sicily was heavily influenced by the Arab candymakers in the 9th century, and Sicilian candy has preserved more of that influence than almost any other place in Europe.&lt;ref name=&quot;:0&quot;&gt;{{cite book |last=Richardson |first=Tim H. |title=Sweets: A History of Candy |publisher=Bloomsbury USA |year=2002 |isbn=1-58234-229-6 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/sweets00timr/page/362 362–364] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/sweets00timr/page/362 }}&lt;/ref&gt;  Marzipan fruits may have been invented at the [[Convent of Eloise at Martorana]] in the 14th century.  In the 17th and 18th centuries, many Sicilian monasteries produced candies and pastries, some with sexual or fertility themes.  The only surviving convent to follow this tradition is the Monastery of the [[Virgins of Palermo]], which makes breast-shaped cakes in honor of St [[Agatha of Sicily]].&lt;ref name=&quot;:0&quot; /&gt;
[[File:Cassata 2.jpg|thumb|[[Cassata]]s are popular and traditional Sicilian [[dessert]]s.|alt=A round, decorated cake|left]]
Traditional sugar statues, called ''pupa di cena'', are still made, although now featuring modern celebrities or culture figures.&lt;ref name=&quot;:0&quot; /&gt;
[[File:Granita brioche.JPG|right|thumb|An almond [[granita]] with brioche|alt=A frozen white dessert in a clear glass, next to a piece of bread]]
Granita is particularly famous and well known. It is a semi-frozen dessert of sugar, water, and flavorings originally from the island, and is commonly associated with [[Messina]] or [[Catania]], even though there is no evident proof that it hails from any particular Sicilian city. Related to [[sorbet]] and [[italian ice]], in most of Sicily it has a coarser, more crystalline texture. Food writer [[Jeffrey Steingarten]] says that &quot;the desired texture seems to vary from city to city&quot; on the island; on the west coast and in [[Palermo]], it is at its chunkiest, and in the east it is nearly as smooth as [[sorbet]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|author=Steingarten, Jeffrey|title=The Man Who Ate Everything|chapter=The Mother of All Ice Cream|pages=361&amp;ndash;380|year=1997|publisher=Vintage Books|isbn=0-375-70202-4}} The chapter is an essay first published in June 1996.&lt;/ref&gt; This is largely the result of different freezing techniques: the smoother types are produced in a [[ice cream maker|gelato machine]], while the coarser varieties are frozen with only occasional agitation, then scraped or shaved to produce separated crystals.

===Fruits===
[[File:Blood oranges.jpg|thumb|right|[[Blood orange#Tarocco|Tarocco]] blood oranges|alt=A plate showing three blood oranges:  one whole, one peeled, and one sliced in half]]
Citrus fruits are a popular ingredient in Sicilian cuisine. Many were first introduced by the [[Arabs]] from the 9th to 11th centuries, but some, such as the Washington navel from [[Brazil]], have been brought to the island more recently. Examples of citrus fruits found in Sicily are :&lt;ref&gt;Piras, Claudia and Medagliani, Eugenio. ''Culinaria Italy''. Cologne: Könemann Verlagsgesellschaft mbh, 2000. pages 440-441.&lt;/ref&gt;
* ''Biondo comune'' - the &quot;common blonde&quot; orange
* ''Ovale'' - ripens between April and May, with a compact flesh
* ''Sanguigno comune'' - common blood orange harvested between January and April
* Washington navel - introduced from [[Brazil]] during the 1940s-1950s, grown chiefly near [[Ribera, Agrigento|Ribera]] and [[Sciacca]] and harvested from November to January
* ''Sanguinella'' - bitter orange of the [[blood orange]] variety, found in Paternò Santa Maria di Licodia, [[Palagonia]], [[Scordia]] and [[Francofonte]] during January until April
* ''[[Blood orange#Tarocco|Tarocco]]'' - high quality blood orange found in [[Catania]], [[Syracuse, Sicily|Siracusa]] and Francofonte from November to January
* ''Tarocco dal muso'' - bell shaped orange found in Francofonte
* ''[[Valencia orange|Valencia]]'' - similar to the Ovale and used often in [[confectionery]] items
* ''Moro'' - crimson colored flesh found in [[Lentini]], Scordia, and Francofonte from mid-January until the end of April
* ''Comune'' - common variety of the [[mandarin orange]]
* ''Tardivo ciaculli'' - a second variety of the mandarin orange found in Sicily
* ''Femminello'' - the lemon that makes up 80% of Sicily's lemon crop, sound in Catania, Siracusa, [[Messina]] and Palermo
* ''Monachello'' - &quot;little monk&quot;'' lemon harvested from October from March and able to withstand drought better that the Ferrminello
* ''Verdello'' - a lime that grows particularly well and is harvested from May to September

===Wines and drinks===
[[File:SIMAL limoncello jp.jpg|thumb|229x229px| [[Limoncello]] is a popular and strong lemon liqueur.|alt=A yellow liquor bottle next to the yellow packaging it is sold in]]

The drink most often served with the main meal in Sicily is [[wine]]. The soil and climate in Sicily are ideal for [[Viticulture|growing grapes]], mainly due to [[Mount Etna]], and a wine-making tradition on the island has existed since the Greeks first set up colonies on the island. Today, all Sicilian provinces produce wine and Sicilian wine produced by modern methods has established itself on the European wine market.

Sicilian [[red wine]]s have an alcoholic content of 12.5 to 13.5% and are usually drunk in the evening with roast or grilled meat. Well-known red wines include the [[Cerasuolo di Vittoria]] and the [[Nero d'Avola]], mainly those produced around Noto (Siracusa). The dry and [[white wine]]s and [[rosé]]s usually have an alcoholic content from 11.5 to 12.5% and are mainly consumed with fish, poultry and pasta dishes.  Various [[dessert wine]]s are also produced, such as the famous [[Marsala (wine)|Marsala]] and the [[Malvasia delle Lipari]].

Other typical Sicilian alcoholic drinks are the [[limoncello]], a lemon liqueur, and the [[Amaro Averna|Amaro Siciliano]], a herbal drink, which is often consumed after meals as a [[digestif|digestive]].

===Street food===
[[File:Arancini.jpg|thumb|text-top|[[Arancini]] from [[Ragusa, Sicily]]. Arancini are fried or (less often) baked rice balls usually filled with [[ragù]] (meat sauce), [[tomato sauce]], [[mozzarella]] or [[pea]]s, and then coated in bread crumbs.|right]]
Sicilians eat large quantities of street food, including the renowned [[arancini]] (a form of [[Deep frying|deep-fried]] rice [[croquette]]s).  Throughout the [[Palermo]] region are found [[pani ca meusa]] and pane con [[panelle]], while in the [[Catania]] region Cartocciate and Cipolline are very popular, and finally in the [[Messina]] region Focaccia messinese and Pitone messinese are common.

