'''Łódź''' ({{IPA-pl|wutɕ|lang|Pl-łódź.ogg}}), written in English as '''Lodz''',{{efn|{{IPAc-en|lang|pron|l|ɒ|d|z}} {{respell|LODZ}}, &lt;small&gt;also&lt;/small&gt; {{IPAc-en|US|w|uː|tʃ|,_|l|uː|dʒ}} {{respell|WOOCH|,_|LOOJ}} &lt;small&gt;and&lt;/small&gt; {{IPAc-en|UK|w|ʊ|tʃ}} {{respell|WUUCH}}.&lt;ref&gt;[https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/us/Lodz &quot;Łódź&quot;] (US) and {{Cite Oxford Dictionaries|Łódź|accessdate=16 September 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite Merriam-Webster|Lodz|accessdate=16 September 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/amp/english/lodz|title=Łódź|work=[[Collins English Dictionary]]|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|accessdate=16 September 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite American Heritage Dictionary|Łódź|accessdate=11 April 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;}} is the third-largest city in [[Poland]] and a former industrial centre. Located in the central part of the country, it has a population of 679,941 (2019).&lt;ref name=&quot;population&quot; /&gt; It is the capital of [[Łódź Voivodeship]], and is located approximately {{convert|120|km|mi}} south-west of [[Warsaw]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://www.trasa.info/wyznaczanie-trasy/lodz-warszawa|title=Łódź - Warszawa trasa i odległość na mapie • dojazd PKP, BUS, PKS|website=www.trasa.info|accessdate=2 August 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt; The city's [[coat of arms]] is an example of [[canting arms|canting]], as it depicts a boat ({{lang|pl|łódź}} in [[Polish language|Polish]]), which alludes to the city's name.

Łódź was once a small settlement that first appeared in 14th-century records. Despite being granted [[city rights|town rights]] in 1423, it remained the private property of the [[Kuyavia]]n bishops and clergy until the late 18th century. The [[Second Industrial Revolution]] brought rapid growth in textile manufacturing and in population due to the inflow of migrants, notably Germans and Jews. Ever since the industrialization of the area, the city has struggled with [[Multinational state|multinationalism]] and social inequalities, which were documented in the novel ''[[The Promised Land (novel)|The Promised Land]]'' by [[Nobel Prize]]-winning author [[Władysław Reymont]]. The contrasts greatly reflected on the architecture of the city, where luxurious mansions coexisted with redbrick factories and dilapidated tenement houses.&lt;ref name=&quot;staypoland.com&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.staypoland.com/about_lodz.htm|title=Lodz – Tourism {{!}} Tourist Information – Lodz, Poland| publisher=eTravel S.A.| date=|website=staypoland.com}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The industrial development and demographic surge made Łódź one of the largest cities in Poland. Under the German occupation during [[World War II]], Łódź was briefly renamed to ''Litzmannstadt'' in honour of [[Karl Litzmann]]. The city's large Jewish population was forced into a walled zone known as the [[Łódź Ghetto]], from which they were sent to German [[Nazi concentration camps|concentration and extermination camps]]. The city itself sustained insignificant&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://miastol.pl/uniwersytet-dla-robotniczej-lodzi/|title=Uniwersytet dla robotniczej Łodzi|first=Marta|last=Madejska|date=2 November 2017|accessdate=27 October 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt; structural damage during the war and became Poland's temporary seat of power in 1945.

Łódź experienced a sharp demographic and economic decline after 1989. It was only in the 2010s that the city began to experience revitalization of its neglected downtown area.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |last1=Cysek-Pawlak |first1=Monika |last2=Krzysztofik |first2=Sylwia |date=2017 |title=Integrated Approach as a Means of Leading the Degraded Post-Industrial Areas Out of Crisis - A Case Study of Lodz |journal= IOP Conference Series: Materials Science and Engineering |volume=245 |issue=8 |pages=082036 |doi=10.1088/1757-899X/245/8/082036 |issn= 1757-8981 |eissn= 1757-899X |bibcode=2017MS&amp;E..245h2036C |doi-access=free }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name= &quot;revit&quot; /&gt; Łódź is ranked by the [[Globalization and World Cities Research Network]] on the “Sufficiency” level of global influence&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=The World According to GaWC 2020 |url=https://www.lboro.ac.uk/gawc/world2020t.html |website=GaWC - Research Network |publisher=Globalization and World Cities |accessdate=3 September 2020}}&lt;/ref&gt; and is internationally known for its [[National Film School in Łódź|National Film School]], a cradle for the most renowned Polish actors and directors, including [[Andrzej Wajda]] and [[Roman Polanski]].&lt;ref name=&quot;staypoland.com&quot;/&gt; In 2017, the city was inducted into the [[UNESCO]] [[Creative Cities Network]] and named UNESCO [[City of Film]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://thenews.pl/1/11/Artykul/333180,Poland%E2%80%99s-Lodz-named-UNESCO-City-of-Film &quot;Poland’s Łódź named UNESCO City of Film.&quot;] Radio Poland. Retrieved 3 November 2017.&lt;/ref&gt;

==History==
{{main|History of Łódź}}
{{see also|Timeline of Łódź}}
[[File:Lodz1577.jpg|thumb|left|150px|''Sigillum oppidi Lodzia'' - seal dating back to 1577]]
Łódź first appears in the written record in a 1332 document giving the village of ''Łodzia'' to the bishops of [[Bishopric of Włocławek|Włocławek]]. In 1423 King [[Jogaila|Władysław II Jagiełło]] officially granted [[Magdeburg rights|city rights]] to the village of ''Łódź''. From then until the 18th century the town remained a small settlement on a [[trade route]] between the provinces of [[Masovia]] and [[Silesia]]. In the 16th century the town had fewer than 800 inhabitants, mostly working on the surrounding grain farms.

With the [[Second Partition of Poland|second partition of Poland]] in 1793, Łódź became part of the [[Kingdom of Prussia]]'s province of [[South Prussia]], and was known in German as ''Lodsch''. In 1798 the Prussians nationalised the town, and it lost its status as a town of the bishops of [[Kuyavia]]. In 1806 Łódź joined the Napoleonic [[Duchy of Warsaw]] and in 1810 it had approximately 190 inhabitants. After the 1815 [[Congress of Vienna]] treaty it became part of the [[Congress Kingdom of Poland]], a [[client state]] of the [[Russian Empire]].

===Century of partitions: 1815 Congress of Vienna===
{{multiple image
 | align = right
 | direction = vertical
 | width = 200
 | header = 
 | image1 = Synagoga i pacac Herza Lodz.jpg
 | alt1 = Synagogue
 | caption1 = The [[Great Synagogue (Łódź)|Great Synagogue]] was the main prayer house for the local [[History of the Jews in Poland|Jewish community]]. It was destroyed during [[World War II]]
 | image2 = Kamienica Mieczyslawa Pinkusa.jpg
 | alt2 = Tenement house of Mieczysław Pinkus in Łódź, ca. 1986
 | caption2 = Many [[Tenement|tenement houses]] often reflected the social status of owners and industrialists
}}
In the 1815 treaty, it was planned to renew the dilapidated town and with the 1816 decree by the Czar a number of German immigrants received territory deeds for them to clear the land and to build factories and housing. Their incentives for settlement included &quot;exemption from tax obligations for a period of six years, free materials to build houses, perpetual lease of land for construction, exemption from military service or duty-free transport of the immigrants’ livestock.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=https://www.centrumdialogu.com/en/niemiecka-lodz| title=German Łódź| publisher=Centrum Dialogu (Dialog Center)| access-date=2019-05-09}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 1820 [[Stanisław Staszic]] aided in changing the small town into a modern industrial centre. The immigrants came to the ''Promised Land'' (''Ziemia obiecana'', the city's nickname) from all over Europe. Mostly they arrived from [[Saxony]], [[Silesia]] and [[Bohemia]], but also from countries as far away as Portugal, England, France and Ireland.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} The first [[cotton mill]] opened in 1825, and 14 years later the very first [[steam engine|steam-powered]] factory in both Poland and the Russian Empire commenced operations. In 1839, over 78% of the population was German,&lt;ref name=&quot;Muller&quot;&gt;Wiesław Puś, Stefan Pytlas. &quot;Industry and Trade in Łódź and the Eastern Markets in Partitioned Poland&quot;. In: Uwe Müller, Helga Schultz. ''National borders and economic disintegration in modern East Central Europe.'' Berlin Verlag A. Spitz. 2002. p. 69.&lt;/ref&gt; and German schools and churches were established.

A constant influx of workers, businessmen and craftsmen from all over Europe transformed Łódź into the main textile production centre of the mighty Russian Empire spanning from [[East-Central Europe]] all the way to [[Alaska]]. As long as the town was small, the majority of the town's population was German speaking.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book| chapter=Nachbarn, Fremde, Okkupanten: Die Deutschen im unabhängigen und besetzten Polen (1919-44)| author=Włodzimierz Borodziej| title=Als der Osten noch Heimat war| publisher=Rowohls Taschenbuch Verlag}}&lt;/ref&gt; Three groups then dominated the city's population and contributed the most to the city's development: Germans, Poles, and Jews, who started to arrive from 1848. Many of the Łódź craftspeople were [[Weaving|weavers]] from [[Upper Silesia|Upper]] and [[Lower Silesia]].

In 1850, Russia abolished the customs barrier between [[Congress Poland]] and Russia proper and therefore industry in Łódź could now develop freely with a huge Russian market not far away. Eventually the city became the second-largest city of Congress Poland. In 1865 the first railroad line opened (to [[Koluszki]], branch line of the [[Warsaw–Vienna railway]]), and soon the city had rail links with Warsaw and [[Białystok]].

{{multiple image
 | align = left
 | direction = vertical
